children.name: hwEthernetTable
children.description: Indicates the physical attributes of the Ethernet interface. This table lists the physical attributes of various Ethernet interfaces.

children.name: hwEthernetEntry
children.description: Indicates the physical attributes of the Ethernet interface. This table lists the physical attributes of various Ethernet interfaces.

children.name: hwEthernetIfIndex
children.description: Interface index(es) of port(s) present on the device .

children.name: hwEthernetLoopback
children.description: The local loopback of an Ethernet interface is used to test the interface itself. If an interface works in a normal situation, disable the local loopback. By default, stopLoopback is used. Enumeration: 'otherLoop': 1, 'stopLoopback': 2, 'local': 3, 'remote': 4.

children.name: hwEthernetPortType
children.description: Indicates the type of the Ethernet interface: an optical interface or an electrical interface. Enumeration: 'copper': 2, 'other': 1, 'fiber': 3.

children.name: hwEthernetSpeedSet
children.description: Indicates the speed of the Ethernet interface. This parameter takes effect only on some Ethernet electrical interfaces rather than optical interfaces. The parameter can be 10 M, 100 M, 1000 M, 10000 M. Enumeration: 'speed10000': 5, 'speed10': 2, 'speed100': 3, 'other': 1, 'speed1000': 4.

children.name: hwEthernetDuplex
children.description: Indicates the duplex mode of the Ethernet interface. An electrical Ethernet interface can work in half-duplex mode or full-duplex mode. An optical Ethernet can work only in full-duplex mode. Enumeration: 'full': 1, 'half': 2.

children.name: hwEthernetNegotiation
children.description: Indicates the auto-negotiation mode of the Ethernet electrical interface. By default, auto-negotiation is enabled. The three objects, hwEthernetSpeedSet, hwEthernetDuplex, and hwEthernetNegotiation are associated with each other. If the auto-negotiation of hwEthernetNegotiation is enabled, the values of hwEthernetSpeedSet and hwEthernetDuplex are auto-negotiated. If hwEthernetSpeedSet is set to a certain value, hwEthernetDuplex is modified to the default value full, and hwEthernetNegotiation is automatically changed to disable. If the auto-negotiation of hwEthernetNegotiation is enabled, hwEthernetDuplex cannot be set.

children.name: hwEthernetPortTypeOperate
children.description: Indicates the link type of the Ethernet interface. The type can be optical link or electrical link. This parameter takes effect only on specific Ethernet interfaces. Enumeration: 'fiber1000': 4, 'copper': 2, 'fiber100': 3, 'other': 1.

children.name: hwEthernetClock
children.description: Indicates the mode of the clock. The mode can be master or slave. By default, the mode of a clock is slave. This parameter takes effect only on the WAN board. Enumeration: 'slave': 2, 'master': 1.

children.name: hwEthernetFlagJ0Mode
children.description: Before the 10 GE WAN board processes packets, the overhead byte must be configured on the interface. The overhead byte for the SDH frame, j0: Set section trace byte The default value is j016ByteMode(2)hwEthernetFlagJ0Trace NetEngine Enumeration: 'peer': 4, 'j064ByteOrNullMode': 3, 'j016ByteMode': 2, 'j01ByteMode': 1.

children.name: hwEthernetFlagJ0Value
children.description: j01ByteMode Value. When hwEthernetFlagJ0Mode is set to j01ByteMode, this parameter takes effect.

children.name: hwEthernetFlagJ0Trace
children.description: Set section trace byte. When hwEthernetFlagJ0Mode is set to j016ByteMode or j064ByteOrNullMode, this variable takes effect. When hwEthernetFlagJ0Mode is set to j016ByteMode, this variable is up to 15 characters trace byte. When hwEthernetFlagJ0Mode is set to j064ByteOrNullMode, this variable is up to 64 characters trace byte.

children.name: hwEthernetFlagJ1Mode
children.description: Indicates the overhead byte of the SDH frame. j1sets path trace byte. The default value is j116ByteMode(2) hwEthernetFlagJ1Trace NetEngine. Enumeration: 'j164ByteOrNullMode': 3, 'j116ByteMode': 2, 'j11ByteMode': 1, 'peer': 4.

children.name: hwEthernetFlagJ1Value
children.description: j11ByteMode Value. When hwEthernetFlagJ1Mode is set to j11ByteMode, this parameter takes effect.

children.name: hwEthernetFlagJ1Trace
children.description: Set path trace byte. When hwEthernetFlagJ1Mode is set to j116ByteMode or j164ByteOrNullMode, this variable takes effect. When hwEthernetFlagJ1Mode is set to j116ByteMode, this variable is up to 15 characters trace byte. When hwEthernetFlagJ1Mode is set to j164ByteOrNullMode, this variable is up to 64 characters trace byte.

children.name: hwEthernetFlagC2Value
children.description: Indicates the overhead byte of the SDH frame. c2: indicates the signal label byte. It is a hexdecimal value ranging from 00 to FF. The default value is 0x02.

children.name: hwEthernetUpHoldTime
children.description: Indicates the response time to the event that the port turns Up. The units of hwEthernetUpHoldTime is millisecond.

children.name: hwEthernetDownHoldTime
children.description: Indicates the response time to the event that the port turns Down. The units of hwEthernetDownHoldTime is millisecond.

children.name: hwEthernetSubinterfaceStatisticEnable
children.description: Enable the statistical function of the sub-interface.

children.name: hwPosTable
children.description: Indicates the physical attributes of the POS interface. This table lists the physical attributes of the POS interface.

children.name: hwPosEntry
children.description: Indicates the physical attributes of the POS interface. This table lists the physical attributes of the POS interface.

children.name: hwPosIfIndex
children.description: Interface index(es) of port(s) present on the device .

children.name: hwPosLinkProtocol
children.description: Indicates the link layer protocol of the POS interface. By default, on a POS interface, PPP serves as the link layer protocol. Enumeration: 'ietf': 1, 'ppp': 4, 'nonstandard': 2, 'hdlc': 3.

children.name: hwPosFrameFormat
children.description: Indicates the frame type of the POS interface. By default, the frame type of the POS interface is SDH. This variable identifies whether a SONET or a SDH signal is used across this interface. Enumeration: 'sonet': 1, 'sdh': 2.

children.name: hwPosLoopback
children.description: The local loopback of a POS interface is used to test the interface itself. If an interface works in a normal situation, disable the local loopback. By default, stopLoopback is used. Enumeration: 'otherLoop': 1, 'stopLoopback': 2, 'local': 3, 'remote': 4.

children.name: hwPosScramble
children.description: Indicates the scramble function of payload. By default, the scramble function of payload is enabled.

children.name: hwPosClock
children.description: Indicates whether the clock is in master mode or slave mode. By default, the clock is in slave mode. Enumeration: 'slave': 2, 'master': 1.

children.name: hwPosCrcVerifyCode
children.description: Indicates the length of the CRC verity code. The default value is 32. Enumeration: 'crc32': 2, 'crc16': 1.

children.name: hwPosFlagJ0Mode
children.description: Indicates the overhead byte of the SDH frame. j0: sets section trace byte. The default value is j016ByteMode(2);hwPosFlagJ0Trace NetEngine. Enumeration: 'peer': 4, 'j064ByteOrNullMode': 3, 'j016ByteMode': 2, 'j01ByteMode': 1.

children.name: hwPosFlagJ0Value
children.description: Indicates the value of j01ByteMode. When hwPosFlagJ0Mode is set to j01ByteMode, hwPosFlagJ0Value takes effect.

children.name: hwPosFlagJ0Trace
children.description: Set section trace byte. When hwPosFlagJ0Mode is set to j016ByteMode or j064ByteOrNullMode, this variable takes effect. When hwPosFlagJ0Mode is set to j016ByteMode, the value of this variable is up to 15 characters trace byte. When hwPosFlagJ0Mode is set to j064ByteOrNullMode, the value of this variable is up to 64 characters trace byte.

children.name: hwPosFlagJ1Mode
children.description: Indicates the overhead byte of the SDH frame. j1: sets path trace byte. The default value is j116ByteMode(2);hwPosFlagJ1Trace NetEngine. Enumeration: 'j164ByteOrNullMode': 3, 'j116ByteMode': 2, 'j11ByteMode': 1, 'peer': 4.

children.name: hwPosFlagJ1Value
children.description: Indicates the value of j11ByteMode. When hwPosFlagJ1Mode is set to j11ByteMode, hwPosFlagJ1Value takes effect.

children.name: hwPosFlagJ1Trace
children.description: Set path trace byte. When hwPosFlagJ1Mode is set to j116ByteMode or j164ByteOrNullMode, this variable takes effect. When hwPosFlagJ1Mode is set to j116ByteMode, this variable is up to 15 characters trace byte. When hwPosFlagJ1Mode is set to j164ByteOrNullMode, this variable is up to 64 characters trace byte.

children.name: hwPosFlagC2Value
children.description: Indicates the overhead byte of the SDH frame. c2: indicates the signal label byte. It is a hexdecimal value ranging from 00 to FF. The default value is 0x02.

children.name: hwCposTable
children.description: Indicates the physical attributes of the CPOS interface. This table lists the physical attributes of the CPOS interface.

children.name: hwCposEntry
children.description: Indicates the physical attributes of the CPOS interface. This table lists the physical attributes of the CPOS interface.

children.name: hwCposIfIndex
children.description: Interface index(es) of port(s) present on the device .

children.name: hwCposClock
children.description: Indicates whether the clock is in master mode or slave mode. By default, the clock is in slave mode. Enumeration: 'slave': 2, 'master': 1.

children.name: hwCposIfType
children.description: Indicates the interface type. Enumeration: 'stm1': 1, 'stm16': 2.

children.name: hwCposFrameFormat
children.description: Indicates the frame type of the CPOS interface. By default, the frame type of the CPOS interface is SDH. Enumeration: 'sonet': 1, 'sdh': 2.

children.name: hwCposMultiplex
children.description: Indicates the multiplex mode of the AUG. By default, the multiplex mode of the AUG is au-4. Enumeration: 'au3': 1, 'au4': 2.

children.name: hwCposLoopback
children.description: Indicates the loopback function of the CPOS interface. By default, the loopback function is disabled. Enumeration: 'otherloop': 1, 'stopLoopback': 2, 'local': 3, 'remote': 4.

children.name: hwCposFlagJ0Mode
children.description: Indicates the overhead byte of the SDH frame. j0: sets section trace byte. The default value is j016ByteMode(2);hwCposFlagJ0Trace NetEngine. Enumeration: 'peer': 4, 'j064ByteOrNullMode': 3, 'j016ByteMode': 2, 'j01ByteMode': 1.

children.name: hwCposFlagJ0Value
children.description: j01ByteMode Value . When hwCposFlagJ0Mode is set to j01ByteMode, hwCposFlagJ0Value takes effect.

children.name: hwCposFlagJ0Trace
children.description: Set section trace byte. When hwCposFlagJ0Mode is set to j016ByteMode or j064ByteOrNullMode, this variable takes effect. When hwCposFlagJ0Mode is set to j016ByteMode, this variable is up to 15 characters trace byte. When hwCposFlagJ0Mode is set to j064ByteOrNullMode, this variable is up to 64 characters trace byte.

children.name: hwCposFlagJ1Mode
children.description: Indicates the overhead byte of the SDH frame. j1: sets path trace byte. The default value is j116ByteMode(2);hwCposFlagJ1Trace NetEngine. Enumeration: 'j164ByteOrNullMode': 3, 'j116ByteMode': 2, 'j11ByteMode': 1, 'peer': 4.

children.name: hwCposFlagJ1Value
children.description: Indicates the value of j11ByteMode. When hwCposFlagJ1Mode is set to j11ByteMode, hwCposFlagJ1Value takes effect.

children.name: hwCposFlagJ1Trace
children.description: Set path trace byte. When hwCposFlagJ1Mode is set to j116ByteMode or j164ByteOrNullMode, this variable takes effect. When hwCposFlagJ1Mode is set to j116ByteMode, this variable is a string up to 15 characters trace byte. When hwCposFlagJ1Mode is set to j164ByteOrNullMode, this variable is a string up to 64 characters trace byte.

children.name: hwCposFlagC2Value
children.description: Indicates the overhead byte of the SDH frame. c2: indicates the signal label byte. It is a hexdecimal value ranging from 00 to FF. The default value is 22(0x16).

children.name: hwDs0ChannelBundleTable
children.description: This table is used to bundle timeslots of CE1/CT1 interfaces.

children.name: hwDs0ChannelBundleEntry
children.description: This table is used to bundle timeslots of CE1/CT1 interfaces.

children.name: hwDs0ChannelBundleParentIfIndex
children.description: Indicates the index of the parent interface.

children.name: hwDs0ChannelBundleDs1ChannelId
children.description: Indicates the channel ID.

children.name: hwDs0ChannelBundleId
children.description: Indicates the index number of the channel set.

children.name: hwDs0ChannelBundleIfIndex
children.description: Indicates the index of the serial interface formed by the timeslot binding.

children.name: hwDs0ChannelBundleTimeSlots
children.description: Indicates the number of the range of the timeslot to be bound. The value is an integer ranging from 0 to 31. Multiple timeslots are separated by ','. The range of timeslot is expressed by using '-'. For E1 card mode: If the timeslots are '0-31', it means unframed format, If the timeslots are '0-30', it means framed format, For T1 card mode: If the timeslots are '0-23', it means unframed format, If the timeslots are '0-22', it means framed format, and hwDs0ChannelBundleDs1ChannelId and hwDs0ChannelBundleId should be zero.

children.name: hwDs0ChannelBundleSpeed
children.description: Configures the mode to configure the timeslots. If the parameter 56 k is selected, the timeslots are bound in the mode of N x 56 kbit/s. If the parameter 64 k is selected, the timeslots are bound in the mode of N x 64 kbit/s. The default value is 64kbit/s. Enumeration: 's56': 1, 's64': 2.

children.name: hwDs0ChannelBundleRowStatus
children.description: This variable is used to create or delete an object.

children.name: hwDs1Table
children.description: This table lists all E1/CE1 interfaces or T1/CT1 interfaces. After the mode of E3/CE3 interfaces or T3/CT3 interfaces is set to channelized, this table can be used to create E1/CE1, or T1/CT1, or E3/CE3, or T3/CT3 interfaces.

children.name: hwDs1Entry
children.description: This table lists all E1/CE1 interfaces or T1/CT1 interfaces. After the mode of E3/CE3 interfaces or T3/CT3 interfaces is set to channelized, this table can be used to create E1/CE1, or T1/CT1, or E3/CE3, or T3/CT3 interfaces.

children.name: hwDs1ParentIfIndex
children.description: Indicates the index of the parent interface.

children.name: hwDs1ChannelId
children.description: Indicates the channel ID.

children.name: hwDs1IfIndex
children.description: Indicates the interface index.

children.name: hwDs1ChannelType
children.description: Indicates the interface type. The type can be E1/CE1 or T1/CT1. Enumeration: 'e1': 2, 't1': 1.

children.name: hwDs1IfType
children.description: Indicates the interface tyep. e3: is multiplexed by CE3 interfaces. t3: is multiplexed by CT3 interfaces. cpos: is multiplexed by CPOS interfaces. atm: is multiplexed by ATM interfaces. none: indicates the physical interface. default:none Enumeration: 'none': 255, 'cpos': 3, 't3': 2, 'e3': 1, 'atm': 4.

children.name: hwDs1Channelized
children.description: Indicates the working mode of the interface. true: indicates the channelized mode. false: indicates the clear channel mode. The default is true.

children.name: hwDs1CodeType
children.description: Indicates the code type of the interface. ami: is short for Alternate Mark Inversion. hdb3: is short for High Density Bipolar of Order 3. b8zs: is short for Bipolar with 8-Zero Substitution. Enumeration: 'ami': 1, 'hdb3': 2, 'b8zs': 3.

children.name: hwDs1Clock
children.description: Indicates the clock mode of the interface. master: indicates that the clock works in master mode and uses the internal clock signal. slave: indicates that the clock works in slave mode and uses the line clock signal. Enumeration: 'slave': 2, 'master': 1.

children.name: hwDs1FrameFormat
children.description: Indicates the frame format of the interface. crc4: indicates that the frame format is CRC4. no-crc4: indicates that the frame format is no-CRC4. sf: indicates that the frame format is Super Frame. esf: indicates that the frame format is Extended Super Frame. By default, the frame format of an E1 interface is no-crc4. By default, the frame format of a T1 interface is esf. Enumeration: 'esf': 1, 'crc': 4, 'sf': 2, 'noCrc4': 3.

children.name: hwDs1Cable
children.description: The cable command takes effect only if the E1 interface card uses 75-ohm coaxial cable. The default is short. If no cable is connected, this parameter is displayed as null. Enumeration: 'short': 2, 'long': 1.

children.name: hwDs1Loopback
children.description: Enable the loopback function of the interface. local: enables the local loopback on the interface. remote: enables the remote loopback on the interface. payload: enables the remote payload loopback on the interface. cell: enables the local cell loopback. The local cell loopback is used to test the local physical chip. Enumeration: 'cell': 4, 'remote': 2, 'none': 255, 'local': 1, 'payload': 3.

children.name: hwDs1RowStatus
children.description: This variable is used to create or delete an object.

children.name: hwDs3Table

children.name: hwDs3Entry
children.description: This table lists all E3/CE3 interfaces or all T3/CT3 interfaces.

children.name: hwDs3ParentIfIndex
children.description: Indicates the index of the parent interface.

children.name: hwDs3ChannelId

children.name: hwDs3IfIndex

children.name: hwDs3ChannelType
children.description: Indicates the interface type. The type can be E3/CE3 or T3/CT3. Enumeration: 't3': 1, 'e3': 2.

children.name: hwDs3IfType
children.description: Indicates the parent interface type of the interface. cpos: is multiplexed by CPOS interfaces. none: indicates the interface is a physical interface. The default is none. Enumeration: 'none': 255, 'cpos': 1.

children.name: hwDs3Channelized
children.description: Indicates the working mode of the interface. true: indicates the channelized mode. false: indicates the clear channel mode. The default is true.

children.name: hwDs3Clock
children.description: Indicates the clock mode of the interface. master: indicates that the clock works in master mode and uses the internal clock signal. slave: indicates that the clock works in slave mode and uses the line clock signal. Enumeration: 'slave': 2, 'master': 1.

children.name: hwDs3FrameFormat
children.description: Indicates the frame format of the interface. Enumeration: 'cbitPlcp': 5, 'g751Plcp': 3, 'g751Adm': 2, 'm23Adm': 6, 'cbitAdm': 4, 'm23Plcp': 7, 'g832Adm': 1.

children.name: hwDs3Scramble
children.description: Indicates the scramble function of the interface. true: enables the scramble function. false: disables the scramble function. The default is false.

children.name: hwDs3Cable
children.description: The cable command takes effect only if the E3 interface card uses 75-ohm coaxial cable. The default is short. If no cable is connected, this parameter is displayed as null. Enumeration: 'short': 2, 'long': 1.

children.name: hwDs3NationalBit
children.description: Indicates the national bit of the E3/CE3 interface. n0: indicates the national bit is 0 and the interface supports only the communication within a country. n1: indicates the national bit is 1 and the interface supports the international communication.  Enumeration: 'n0': 1, 'n1': 2.

children.name: hwDs3Loopback
children.description: Enable the loopback function of the interface. local: enables the local loopback on the interface. remote: enables the remote loopback on the interface. payload: enables the remote payload loopback on the interface. cell: enables the local cell loopback. The local cell loopback is used to test the local physical chip. Enumeration: 'cell': 4, 'remote': 2, 'none': 255, 'local': 1, 'payload': 3.

children.name: hwFwNetEventsTableLastRow
children.description: The index value of the last row in the hwFwNetEventsTable. This number starts at 1 and increase by one with each new log entry. When this number wraps, all events are deleted.

children.name: hwFwBasicEventsTableLastRow
children.description: The index value of the most recently created row in the cfwBasicEventsTable. This number starts at 1 and increase by one with each new log entry. When this number wraps, all events are deleted.

children.name: hwFwBasicEventsTable
children.description: Table of basic data for firewall events. The agent may choose to delete the instances of cfwBasicEventsEntry as required because of lack of memory. The oldest Events will be selected first for deletion.

children.name: hwFwBasicEventsEntry
children.description: An entry in the table, containing general information about an event. This table will always be sparse, i.e., each row will instanciate only a subet of the columnar objects.

children.name: hwFwBasicEventIndex
children.description: An index that uniquely identifies an entry in the log table. These indices are assigned beginning with 1 and increase by one with each new event logged.

children.name: hwFwBasicEventTime
children.description: The time that the event occurred.

children.name: hwFwBasicSecurityEventType
children.description: The type of security-related event that this row contains. If the event is not security-related this object will not be instantiated.

children.name: hwFwBasicEventDescription
children.description: A description of the event. The value of the object may be a zero-length string.

children.name: hwFwBasicEventDetailsTableRow
children.description: A pointer to a row in the table containing details about this event. Generally, the table will be the cfwNetEventsTable but a Cisco-defined table may also appear here. If there there is no more detailed information for this event the value of this object will have the value {0 0}.

children.name: hwFwNetEventsTable
children.description: Table of detailed data for network events. The agent may choose to delete the instances of hwFwBasicEventsEntry as required because of lack of memory. It is an implementation-specific matter as to when this deletion may occur. It is recommended that the oldest log instances are deleted first.

children.name: hwFwNetEventsEntry
children.description: An entry in the table, containing detailed information about an event. Note that this table may be sparse. If Network Address Translation is not enabled hwFwNetEventInsideSrcIpAddress and hwFwNetEventInsideDstIpAddress will not be instantiated in the row. If Port Address Translation is not enabled hwFwNetEventInsideSrcIpPort and hwFwNetEventInsideDstIpPort will not be instantiated in the row. Entries are added to this table at the same time that events are added to the hwFwBasicEventsTable. These two tables may be configured to be different sizes so there may not be a one-to-one correspondence between rows in the two tables.

children.name: hwFwNetEventIndex
children.description: An index that uniquely identifies an entry in the log table. These indices are assigned beginning with one and increase by one with each new log entry. When this number wraps, all events are deleted in order to allow the NMS to differentiate between old and new events.

children.name: hwFwNetEventInterface
children.description: The interface most closely associated with this event. For example, for an event that relates to the receipt of a packet, this object identifies the interface on which the packet was received. If there are multiple interfaces associated with an event, the interface most closely associated with the cause of the event will be used. For example, for an event for the setup of a TCP connection, the interface on the initiator's side of the connection would be preferred. If there is no associated interface, then this object has the value zero.

children.name: hwFwNetEventSrcVrfName
children.description: This object indicates the VRF's name.

children.name: hwFwNetEventSrcIpAddress
children.description: Source IP address in the IP packet that caused the event. If there is no packet associated with the event this object has the value of zero. If the event is the result of multiple packets with different source addresses, this value may be zero or an address taken from an arbitrarily chosen packet in the sequence of packets causing the event.

children.name: hwFwNetEventInsideSrcIpAddress
children.description: Source IP address after Network Address Translation has been applied. If NAT has not been applied to the source address in this packet this object will not be instantiated, resulting in a sparse table. If the event is the result of multiple packets with different source addresses, this value may be zero or an address taken from an arbitrarily chosen packet in the sequence of packets causing the event.

children.name: hwFwNetEventDstVrfName
children.description: This object indicates the VRF's name.

children.name: hwFwNetEventDstIpAddress
children.description: Destination IP address in the IP packet that caused the event. If there is no packet associated with the event this object has the value of zero. If the event is the result of multiple packets with different destination addresses, this value may be zero or an address taken from an arbitrarily chosen packet in the sequence of packets causing the event.

children.name: hwFwNetEventInsideDstIpAddress
children.description: Destination IP address after Network Address Translation has been applied. If NAT has not been applied to the destination address in this packet this object will not be instantiated, resulting in a sparse table. If the event is the result of multiple packets with different destination addresses, this value may be zero or an address taken from an arbitrarily chosen packet in the sequence of packets causing the event.

children.name: hwFwNetEventSrcIpPort
children.description: Source UDP/TCP port in the IP packet that caused the event. If there is no packet associated with the event this object has the value of zero. If the event is the result of multiple packets with different source ports, this value may be zero or a port taken from an arbitrarily chosen packet in the sequence of packets causing the event.

children.name: hwFwNetEventInsideSrcIpPort
children.description: Source UDP/TCP port after Port Address Translation has been applied. If PAT has not been applied to the source port in this packet this object will not be instantiated, resulting in a sparse table. If the event is the result of multiple packets with different source ports, this value may be zero or a port taken from an arbitrarily chosen packet in the sequence of packets causing the event.

children.name: hwFwNetEventDstIpPort
children.description: Destination UDP/TCP port in the IP packet that caused the event. If there is no packet associated with the event this object has the value of zero. If the event is the result of multiple packets with different destination ports, this value may be zero or a port taken from an arbitrarily chosen packet in the sequence of packets causing the event.

children.name: hwFwNetEventInsideDstIpPort
children.description: Destination UDP/TCP port after Port Address Translation has been applied. If PAT has not been applied to the Destination port in this packet this object will not be instantiated, resulting in a sparse table. If the event is the result of multiple packets with different destination ports, this value may be zero or a port taken from an arbitrarily chosen packet in the sequence of packets causing the event.

children.name: hwFwNetEventService
children.description: The identification of the type of service involved with this event.

children.name: hwFwNetEventServiceInformation
children.description: Specific service information. This can be used to describe the particular service indentified by hwFwNetEventService and can reflect whether the service is a local service or a gateway service. For example, if the value for hwFwNetEventService is loginTelnet then the string provided might be 'local telnet'.

children.name: hwNTP
children.description: This MIB provides mechanisms to monitor a NTP server.

children.name: hwNTPSysLeap
children.description: Leap Indicator (LI): This is a two-bit code warning of an impending leap second to be inserted/deleted in the last minute of the current day, with bit 0 and bit 1, respectively, coded as follows: 00, no warning 01, last minute has 61 seconds 10, last minute has 59 seconds) 11, alarm condition (clock not synchronized). Enumeration: 'addSecond': 1, 'noWarning': 0, 'alarm': 3, 'subtractSecond': 2.

children.name: hwNTPSysStratum
children.description: This is an eight-bit integer indicating the stratum level of the local clock, with values defined as follows: 0, unspecified 1, primary reference (e.g.,, radio clock) 2-255, secondary reference (via NTP)

children.name: hwNTPSysPrecision
children.description: Precision : This is a signed integer indicating the precision of the various clocks, in seconds to the nearest power of two. The value must be rounded to the next larger power of two; for instance, a 50-Hz (20 ms) or 60-Hz (16.67ms) power-frequency clock would be assigned the value -5 (31.25 ms), while a 1000-Hz (1 ms) crystal-controlled clock would be assigned the value -9 (1.95 ms).

children.name: hwNTPSysRootdelay
children.description: Root Delay : This is a signed fixed-point number indicating the total roundtrip delay to the primary reference source at the root of the synchronization subnet, in seconds. Note that this variable can take on both positive and negative values, depending on clock precision and skew.

children.name: hwNTPSysRootdispersion
children.description: Root Dispersion : This is a signed fixed-point number indicating the maximum error relative to the primary reference source at the root of the synchronization subnet, in seconds. Only positive values greater than zero are possible.

children.name: hwNTPSysRefid
children.description: Reference Clock Identifier : This is a 32-bit code identifying the particular reference clock. In the case of stratum 0 (unspecified) or stratum 1 (primary reference source), this is a four-octet, left-justified, zero-padded ASCII string. Stratum, Code, Meaning 0, DCN, DCN routing protocol 0, TSP, TSP time protocol 1, ATOM, Atomic clock (calibrated) 1, WWVB, WWVB LF (band 5) radio 1, GOES, GOES UHF (band 9) satellite 1, WWV, WWV HF (band 7) radio

children.name: hwNTPSysReftime
children.description: Reference Timestamp : This is the local time, in timestamp format, when the local clock was last updated. If the local clock has never been synchronized, the value is zero.

children.name: hwNTPSysPoll
children.description: Poll Interval : This is a signed integer indicating the minimum interval between transmitted messages, in seconds as a power of two. For instance, a value of six indicates a minimum interval of 64 seconds.

children.name: hwNTPSysPeer
children.description: This is a selector identifying the current synchronization source. Usually this will be a pointer to a structure containing the peer variables. The special value NULL indicates There is no currently valid synchronization source.

children.name: hwNTPSysState
children.description: This is a integer indicating the state of local clock. Enumeration: 'noUpdateClock': 0, 'clockBySyns': 4, 'findError': 5, 'getfreqInfo': 1, 'clockBySet': 2, 'clockBySetAndNoFreq': 3.

children.name: hwNTPSysOffset
children.description: The offset of two clocks is the time difference between them.

children.name: hwNTPSysDrift
children.description: Real clocks exhibit some variation in skew (second derivative of offset with time), which is called drift.

children.name: hwNTPSysCompliance
children.description: This is a string indicating the system error.

children.name: hwNTPSysClock
children.description: This is the current local time, in timestamp format. Local time is derived from the hardware clock of the particular machine and increments at intervals depending on the design used.

children.name: hwNTPSysStabil
children.description: This is a indicating that stability of a clock is how well it can maintain a constant frequency.

children.name: hwNTPSysAuthenticate
children.description: This is a integer indicating that system support authentication. Enumeration: 'authenticate': 1, 'noAuthenticate': 0.

children.name: hwNTPSysPollSec
children.description: PollSec Interval : This is a integer indicating the minimum interval between transmitted messages. For instance, a value of six indicates a minimum interval of 6 seconds.

children.name: hwNTPSysClockSec
children.description: This is the current local time, in integer format. Local time is derived from the hardware clock of the particular machine and increments at intervals depending on the design used.

children.name: hwNTPServerIP
children.description: The NTP server ip address. It must be a unicast address, rather than a broadcast address, a multicast address or the IP address of the local clock. To delete a configured NTP server ip address, please set hwNTPServerIP to 0.

children.name: hwNTPPeerTable
children.description: This table provides information on the peers with which the local NTP server has associations. The peers are also NTP servers but running on different hosts.

children.name: hwNTPPeerEntry
children.description: Each peers' entry provides NTP information retrieved from a particular peer NTP server. Each peer is identified by a unique association identifier. Entries are automatically created when the user configures the NTP server to be associated with remote peers. Similarly entries are deleted when the user removes the peer association from the NTP server. Entries can also be created by the management station by setting values for the following objects: hwNTPPeerRemAdr and making the hwNTPPeerRowStatus as 'active'. At the least, the management station has to set a value for hwNTPPeerRemAdr to make the row active.

children.name: hwNTPPeerConfig
children.description: This is a bit indicating that the association was created from configuration information and should not be demobilized if the peer becomes unreachable.

children.name: hwNTPPeerAuthenable
children.description: This is a bit indicating that system support authentication.

children.name: hwNTPPeerAuthentic
children.description: This is a bit indicating that massage pass authentication which is authentic.

children.name: hwNTPPeerRemAdr
children.description: The IP address of the peer. When creating a new association, a value for this object should be set before the row is made active.

children.name: hwNTPPeerRemPort
children.description: The UDP port number on which the peer receives NTP messages.

children.name: hwNTPPeerLocAdr
children.description: The IP address of the local host. Multi-homing can be supported using this object.

children.name: hwNTPPeerLocPort
children.description: The UDP port number on which the local host receives NTP messages.

children.name: hwNTPPeerLeap
children.description: This is a two-bit code warning of an impending leap second to be inserted in the NTP timescale. The bits are set before 23:59 on the day of insertion and reset after 00:00 on the following day. This causes the number of seconds (rollover interval) in the day of insertion to be increased or decreased by one. The two bits are coded as below, 00, no warning 01, last minute has 61 seconds 10, last minute has 59 seconds 11, alarm condition (clock not synchronized) Enumeration: 'addSecond': 1, 'noWarning': 0, 'alarm': 3, 'subtractSecond': 2.

children.name: hwNTPPeerHMode
children.description: This is an integer indicating the association mode, with values coded as follows, 0, unspecified 1, symmetric active - A host operating in this mode sends periodic messages regardless of the reach ability state or stratum of its peer. By operating in this mode the host announces its willingness to synchronize and be synchronized by the peer 2, symmetric passive - This type of association is ordinarily created upon arrival of a message from a peer operating in the symmetric active mode and persists only as long as the peer is reachable and operating at a stratum level less than or equal to the host; otherwise, the association is dissolved. However, the association will always persist until at least one message has been sent in reply. By operating in this mode the host announces its willingness to synchronize and be synchronized by the peer 3, client - A host operating in this mode sends periodic messages regardless of the reach ability state or stratum of its peer. By operating in this mode the host, usually a LAN workstation, announces its willingness to be synchronized by, but not to synchronize the peer 4, server - This type of association is ordinarily created upon arrival of a client request message and exists only in order to reply to that request, after which the association is dissolved. By operating in this mode the host, usually a LAN time server, announces its willingness to synchronize, but not to be synchronized by the peer 5, broadcast - A host operating in this mode sends periodic messages regardless of the reach ability state or stratum of the peers. By operating in this mode the host, usually a LAN time server operating on a high-speed broadcast medium, announces its willingness to synchronize all of the peers, but not to be synchronized by any of them 6, reserved for NTP control messages 7, reserved for private use 8, broadcastclient 9, multicastclient Enumeration: 'multicastclient': 9, 'symmetricActive': 1, 'reservedPrivate': 7, 'reservedControl': 6, 'unspecified': 0, 'server': 4, 'broadcast': 5, 'client': 3, 'broadcastclient': 8, 'symmetricPassive': 2.

children.name: hwNTPPeerStratum
children.description: This is a integer indicating the stratum level of the local clock, with values defined as follows: 0, unspecified 1, primary reference (e.g.,, radio clock) 2-255, secondary reference (via NTP)

children.name: hwNTPPeerPPoll
children.description: The interval at which the peer polls the local host.

children.name: hwNTPPeerHPoll
children.description: The interval at which the local host polls the peer.

children.name: hwNTPPeerPrecision
children.description: This is a signed integer indicating the precision of the peer clock, in seconds to the nearest power of two. The value must be rounded to the next larger power of two; for instance, a 50-Hz (20 ms) or 60-Hz (16.67 ms) power-frequency clock would be assigned the value -5 (31.25 ms), while a 1000-Hz (1 ms) crystal-controlled clock would be assigned the value -9 (1.95 ms).

children.name: hwNTPPeerRootDelay
children.description: This is a signed fixed-point number indicating the total roundtrip delay to the primary reference source at the root of the synchronization subnet, in seconds. Note that this variable can take on both positive and negative values, depending on clock precision and skew.

children.name: hwNTPPeerRootDispersion
children.description: This is a signed fixed-point number indicating the maximum error of the peer clock relative to the primary reference source at the root of the synchronization subnet. Only positive values greater than zero are possible.

children.name: hwNTPPeerRefId
children.description: The reference identifier of the peer. This is a 32-bit code identifying the particular reference clock. In the case of stratum 0 (unspecified) or stratum 1 (primary reference source), this is a four-octet, left-justified, zero-padded ASCII string. Stratum, Code, Meaning 0, DCN, DCN routing protocol 0, TSP, TSP time protocol 1, ATOM, Atomic clock (calibrated) 1, WWVB, WWVB LF (band 5) radio 1, GOES, GOES UHF (band 9) satellite 1, WWV, WWV HF (band 7) radio

children.name: hwNTPPeerRefTime
children.description: This is the local time at the peer, in timestamp format, when the local clock was last updated. If the local clock has never been synchronized, the value is zero.

children.name: hwNTPPeerOrg
children.description: This is the local time, in timestamp format, at the peer when it's latest NTP message was sent. If the peer becomes unreachable the value is set to zero

children.name: hwNTPPeerRec
children.description: This is the local time, in timestamp format, when the latest NTP message from the peer arrived. If the peer becomes unreachable the value is set to zero.

children.name: hwNTPPeerXmt
children.description: This is the local time, in timestamp format, at which the NTP message departed the sender.

children.name: hwNTPPeerReach
children.description: This is a shift register of NTP.WINDOW bits used to determine the reach ability status of the peer, with bits entering from the least significant (rightmost) end. A peer is considered reachable if at least one bit in this register is set to one

children.name: hwNTPPeerValid
children.description: This is an integer counter indicating the valid samples remaining in the filter register. It is used to determine the reach ability state and when the poll interval should be increased or decreased.

children.name: hwNTPPeerTimer
children.description: This is an integer counter used to control the interval of transmitted NTP messages from the local host to the peer.

children.name: hwNTPPeerDelay
children.description: This is a signed fixed-point number indicating the roundtrip delay of the peer clock relative to the local clock over the network path between them, in seconds. Note that this variable can take on both positive and negative values, depending on clock precision and skew-error accumulation.

children.name: hwNTPPeerOffset
children.description: This is a signed, fixed-point number indicating the offset of the peer clock relative to the local clock, in seconds.

children.name: hwNTPPeerJitter
children.description: This is an indicating that peer of sample Variance

children.name: hwNTPPeerDispersion
children.description: This is a signed fixed-point number indicating the maximum error of the peer clock relative to the local clock over the network path between them, in seconds. Only positive values greater than zero are possible.

children.name: hwNTPPeerKeyId
children.description: This is an unsigned integer identifying the cryptographic key used to generate the message-authentication code.

children.name: hwNTPPeerFiltDelay
children.description: Round-trip delay of the peer clock relative to the local clock over the network path between them, in seconds. This variable can take on both positive and negative values, depending on clock precision and skew-error accumulation.

children.name: hwNTPPeerFiltOffset
children.description: The offset of the peer clock relative to the local clock in seconds.

children.name: hwNTPPeerFiltError
children.description: The maximum error of the peer clock relative to the local clock over the network path between them, in seconds. Only positive values greater than zero are possible.

children.name: hwNTPPeerPMode
children.description: This is an integer indicating the association mode, with values coded as follows, 0, unspecified 1, symmetric active - A host operating in this mode sends periodic messages regardless of the reach ability state or stratum of its peer. By operating in this mode the host announces its willingness to synchronize and be synchronized by the peer 2, symmetric passive - This type of association is ordinarily created upon arrival of a message from a peer operating in the symmetric active mode and persists only as long as the peer is reachable and operating at a stratum level less than or equal to the host; otherwise, the association is dissolved. However, the association will always persist until at least one message has been sent in reply. By operating in this mode the host announces its willingness to synchronize and be synchronized by the peer 3, client - A host operating in this mode sends periodic messages regardless of the reach ability state or stratum of its peer. By operating in this mode the host, usually a LAN workstation, announces its willingness to be synchronized by, but not to synchronize the peer 4, server - This type of association is ordinarily created upon arrival of a client request message and exists only in order to reply to that request, after which the association is dissolved. By operating in this mode the host, usually a LAN time server, announces its willingness to synchronize, but not to be synchronized by the peer 5, broadcast - A host operating in this mode sends periodic messages regardless of the reach ability state or stratum of the peers. By operating in this mode the host, usually a LAN time server operating on a high-speed broadcast medium, announces its willingness to synchronize all of the peers, but not to be synchronized by any of them 6, reserved for NTP control messages 7, reserved for private use 8, broadcastclient 9, multicastclient When creating a new peer association, if no value is specified for this object, it defaults to 'symmetricActive'. Enumeration: 'multicastclient': 9, 'symmetricActive': 1, 'reservedPrivate': 7, 'reservedControl': 6, 'unspecified': 0, 'server': 4, 'broadcast': 5, 'client': 3, 'broadcastclient': 8, 'symmetricPassive': 2.

children.name: hwChargeOperStatus
children.description: Charge operation status. Options: 1. average(1) - indicates that the charge operation state is average charge 2. float(2) - indicates that the charge operation state is float charge 3. full(3) - indicates that the charge operation state is full 4. noCharge(4) - indicates that there is no charge in operation 5. discharge(5) - indicates that there is discharge in operation 6. sleep(6) - indicates that the charge operation state is sleep 7. invalid(-1) - indicates that the device can not get the value, e.g. the EMU does not support this operation, or the EMU state is abnormal  Enumeration: 'full': 3, 'average': 1, 'float': 2, 'invalid': -1, 'sleep': 6, 'discharge': 5, 'noCharge': 4.

children.name: hwAverageChargeVoltage
children.description: Voltage value of average charge, in unit of mV. Default: 56500 Unit: mV

children.name: hwFloatChargeVoltage
children.description: Voltage value of float charge . Default: 53500 Unit: mV

children.name: hwChargeControlRowStatus
children.description: RowStatus standard operation

children.name: hwAverageChargeTime
children.description: Timing average charge time interval, effective range is 190 days. Default :value is 60 days Unit: day

children.name: hwBatteryTmpRedeemingQuotiety
children.description: Temperature redeeming quotient, used to set the co-relation between the float charge voltage and the battery temperature. It means How much will the float charge voltage decrease with the increasing of every degree centigrade of the battery temperature. The unit is mV. Specific value is determined by the redeem feature curve of floating charge for the battery group used. Default value is 100mV

children.name: hwBatteryTable
children.description: Battery group state table. Through this table, the status parameter of a battery group can be set and queried. The indexes of this table are hwEnvEmuIndex, hwPowerIndex, and hwBatteryIndex. hwEnvEmuIndex is the index of the monitored unit. hwPowerIndex is the index of the power supply monitored by the monitoring unit. hwBatteryIndex is the index of the monitored battery group.

children.name: hwBatteryEntry
children.description: Battery group state table. Through this table, the status parameter of a battery group can be set and queried. The indexes of this entry are hwEnvEmuIndex, hwPowerIndex, and hwBatteryIndex. hwEnvEmuIndex is the index of the monitored unit. hwPowerIndex is the index of the power supply monitored by the monitoring unit. hwBatteryIndex is the index of the monitored battery group.

children.name: hwBatteryIndex
children.description: Battery group loop index

children.name: hwBatteryCapacity
children.description: The permitted max battery capacity of the battery group loop charge. Unit: Ah

children.name: hwBatteryLoopState
children.description: The battery group present status. Options: 1. on(1) - indicates that the present state of battery group is on 2. off(2) - indicates that the present state of battery group is off 3. invalid(-1) - indicates that the device can not get the value, e.g. the EMU does not support this operation, or the EMU state is abnormal  Enumeration: 'on': 1, 'off': 2, 'invalid': -1.

children.name: hwBatteryVoltage
children.description: The loop voltage of the battery group. Unit: mV

children.name: hwBatteryState
children.description: The present state of the battery group loop. Options: 1. charge(1) - indicates that the present state of the battery group loop is charge 2. discharge(2) - indicates that the present state of the battery group loop is discharge 3. invalid(-1) - indicates that the device can not get the value, e.g. the EMU does not support this operation, or the EMU state is abnormal  Enumeration: 'discharge': 2, 'charge': 1, 'invalid': -1.

children.name: hwBatteryCurrent
children.description: Present current . Unit: mA

children.name: hwBatteryTemperature
children.description: The loop temperature of the battery group. Unit: degree

children.name: hwBatteryRowStatus
children.description: RowStatus standard operation

children.name: hwBatteryCurrentHigh
children.description: The over-current alarm point of the battery group. Unit: mA

children.name: hwBatteryFuseState
children.description: Battery fuse state. Options: 1. on(1) - indicates that the fuse is connected 2. off(2) - indicates that the fuse is disconnected 3. invalid(-1) - indicates that the device can not get the value, e.g. the EMU does not support this operation, or the EMU state is abnormal  Enumeration: 'on': 1, 'off': 2, 'invalid': -1.

children.name: hwBatteryContactState
children.description: The state of the battery contactor. Options: 1. on(1) - indicates that the contactor is connected 2. off(2) - indicates that the contactor is disconnected 3. invalid(-1) - indicates that the device can not get the value, e.g. the EMU does not support this operation, or the EMU state is abnormal Enumeration: 'on': 1, 'off': 2, 'invalid': -1.

children.name: hwBatteryRemainCapacity
children.description: Remain capacity of the battery

children.name: hwBatteryProtectState
children.description: Protection status of the battery. Options: 1. normal(1) - indicates that the Protection status of the battery is normal 2. overtemperature(2) - indicates that the Protection status of the battery is overtemperature 3. overCurrent(3) - indicates that the Protection status of the battery is overCurrent  Enumeration: 'overCurrent': 3, 'overtemperature': 2, 'normal': 1.

children.name: hwBatteryVoltageState
children.description: Voltage state of Battery. Options: 1. normal(1) - indicates that Voltage state of Battery is normal 2. exceedVoltage(2) - indicates that Voltage state of Battery is exceedVoltage 3. belowVoltage(3) - indicates that Voltage state of Battery is belowVoltage  Enumeration: 'belowVoltage': 3, 'exceedVoltage': 2, 'normal': 1.

children.name: hwBatteryHardwareState
children.description: Hardware State of Battery. Options: 1. normal(1) - indicates that the hardware state of Battery is normal 2. fault(2) - indicates that the hardware state of Battery is fault  Enumeration: 'fault': 2, 'normal': 1.

children.name: hwBatteryTestTable
children.description: Battery test table. The indexes of this table are hwEnvEmuIndex and hwPowerIndex. hwEnvEmuIndex is the index of the monitored unit, and hwPowerIndex is the index of the power supply monitored by the monitoring unit.

children.name: hwBatteryTestEntry
children.description: Battery test table. The indexes of this entry are hwEnvEmuIndex and hwPowerIndex. hwEnvEmuIndex is the index of the monitored unit, and hwPowerIndex is the index of the power supply monitored by the monitoring unit.

children.name: hwBatteryTestAdminStatus
children.description: Battery test admin status. Options: 1. start(1) - indicates that the Battery starts testing 2. terminate(2) - indicates that the Battery terminates testing 3. enableAutoTest(3) - indicates that the Battery enables auto test function 4. disableAutoTest(4) - indicates that the Battery disables auto test function 5. timeautoTest(5) - indicates that the Battery enable timing auto test function 6. offautoTest(6) - indicates that the Battery enable off auto test function 7. timeoffautoTest(7) - indicates that the Battery enable timing+off auto test  Enumeration: 'offautoTest': 6, 'timeoffautoTest': 7, 'disableAutoTest': 4, 'terminate': 2, 'start': 1, 'enableAutoTest': 3, 'timeautoTest': 5.

children.name: hwBatteryTestAutoDischargePeriod
children.description: Auto discharge test period. Effective range is 30 -240 days. Default: 120 Unit: day

children.name: hwBatteryTestResult
children.description: Test result: Options: 1. testing(1) - indicates that the Battery test is in operation 2. complete(2) - indicates that the Battery test is completed normally 3. alarmTerminated(3) - indicates that the Battery test is stopped by alarms 4. hostTerminated(4) - indicates that the Battery test is stopped by the host 5. overtimeTerminated(5) - indicates that the Battery test is stopped because of over time 6. normal(6) - indicates that the Battery test is not started 7. supplyRecoverAutotestTerminated(7) - indicates that the Battery test is stopped because of supply recover  Enumeration: 'complete': 2, 'supplyRecoverAutotestTerminated': 7, 'normal': 6, 'testing': 1, 'hostTerminated': 4, 'alarmTerminated': 3, 'overtimeTerminated': 5.

children.name: hwBatteryTestStartTime
children.description: Time of starting test

children.name: hwBatteryTestDuration
children.description: Battery discharge test duration . Effective range is 1-100 hours. Default :value is 10 hours Unit: hour

children.name: hwBatteryTestTerminateVoltage
children.description: Battery discharge test end voltage. Effective range (DC lack alarm voltage+0.5V-voltage of floating charge). Default: 45600 Unit: mV

children.name: hwBatteryTestTotalDischargeAH
children.description: Total discharge AH. Unit: mAH

children.name: hwBatteryTestOperStatus
children.description: Battery discharge test operate status. Options: 1. autoTestPermit(1) - indicates that auto discharge test is enabled 2. autoTestForbid(2) - indicates that auto discharge test is disabled 3. timeautoTestPermit(3) - indicates that timing auto discharge test is enabled 4. offautoTestPermit(4) - indicates that off auto discharge test is enabled 5. timeoffautoTestPermit(5) - indicates that timing-off auto discharge test is enabled Enumeration: 'timeautoTestPermit': 3, 'offautoTestPermit': 4, 'timeoffautoTestPermit': 5, 'autoTestForbid': 2, 'autoTestPermit': 1.

children.name: hwBatteryTestPhase
children.description: Battery test phase. Options: 1. charge(1) - indicates the batter test phase is charge 2. discharge(2) - indicates the batter test phase is discharge 3. record(3) - indicates the power equipment recording test result 4. finish(4) - indicates that the discharge is complete 5.waitingfordischarge(5) - indicates that preparation is ready for discharge command  Enumeration: 'discharge': 2, 'charge': 1, 'finish': 4, 'waitingfordischarge': 5, 'record': 3.

children.name: hwBatteryTestStartHour
children.description: Discharge start time. Effective range is 0 23 Default: 0 Unit: hour

children.name: hwBatteryTestAlarmThreshold
children.description: The battery discharge test alarm threshold in ratio of the range:1~79.

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestTable
children.description: Battery test result table, Through this table, the discharging test result of the battery group can be saved and queried. The indexes of this table are hwEnvEmuIndex, hwPowerIndex, and hwBatteryLogTestIndex. hwEnvEmuIndex is the index of the monitored unit. hwPowerIndex is the index of the power supply monitored by the monitoring unit. hwBatteryLogTestIndex is the index of the monitored battery.

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestEntry
children.description: Battery test result table, Through this table, the discharging test result of the battery group can be saved and queried. The indexes of this entry are hwEnvEmuIndex, hwPowerIndex, and hwBatteryLogTestIndex. hwEnvEmuIndex is the index of the monitored unit. hwPowerIndex is the index of the power supply monitored by the monitoring unit. hwBatteryLogTestIndex is the index of the monitored battery.

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestIndex
children.description: Battery discharge test result index

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestStartTime
children.description: Battery discharge test start time

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestDischargeDuration
children.description: Duration of discharge. Unit: minute

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestTerminateVoltage
children.description: End voltage of battery discharge test . Unit: mV

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestBatteryStatus
children.description: Battery status. Options: 1. expectant(1) - indicates the batter test state is expectant 2. unexpected(2) - indicates the batter test state is unexpected 3. unknown(3) - indicates the batter test state is unknown  Enumeration: 'unknown': 3, 'unexpected': 2, 'expectant': 1.

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestTotalDischargeAH
children.description: Discharge cumulate AH. Unit: mAH

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestFinish
children.description: Battery Test result. Options: 1. testing(1) - indicates that it is during testing 2. completed(2) - indicates that the test is completed normally 3. alarmTerminated(3) - indicates that the test is stopped by alarms 4. hostTerminated(4) - indicates that the test is stopped by the host 5. overtimeTerminated(5) - indicates that the test is stopped because of over 100 hours 6. notTest(6) - indicates that the test is not started  Enumeration: 'alarmTerminated': 3, 'completed': 2, 'testing': 1, 'hostTerminated': 4, 'notTest': 6, 'overtimeTerminated': 5.

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestEfficiency
children.description: The information of battery test efficiency.

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestBatteryTemperature
children.description: Battery discharge test end Temperature. Unit: 0.01 Degree

children.name: hwBatteryLogTestBatteryCurrent
children.description: Battery discharge test average Current. Unit: mA

children.name: hwRemoteProvidePowerInfoTable
children.description: Remote provide power basic information table. The indexes of this table are hwEnvEmuIndex and hwPowerIndex. hwEnvEmuIndex is the index of the monitored unit, and hwPowerIndex is the index of the power supply monitored by the monitoring unit.

children.name: hwRemoteProvidePowerInfoEntry
children.description: Remote provide power basic information table. The indexes of this entry are hwEnvEmuIndex and hwPowerIndex. hwEnvEmuIndex is the index of the monitored unit, and hwPowerIndex is the index of the power supply monitored by the monitoring unit.

children.name: hwPowerCentralState
children.description: State of the central module. Options: 1. normal(1) - indicates the normal state 2. temOver(2) - indicates the over-temperature  Enumeration: 'temOver': 2, 'normal': 1.

children.name: hwPowerCentralDCInPutState
children.description: State of central module DC input: Options: 1.normal(1) - indicates the normal state 2.lack(2) - indicates the voltage underflow 3.over(3) - indicates the voltage overflow  Enumeration: 'over': 3, 'lack': 2, 'normal': 1.

children.name: hwPowerCentralDCOutputState
children.description: State of central module DC output. Options: 1. normal(1) - indicates the normal state 2. volLack(2) - indicates the voltage underflow 3. volOver(3) - indicates the voltage overflow 4. loadOver(4) - indicates the over-loading 5. shortCircuit(5) - indicates the short circuit 6. noLoad(6) - indicates no load  Enumeration: 'volOver': 3, 'normal': 1, 'loadOver': 4, 'shortCircuit': 5, 'noLoad': 6, 'volLack': 2.

children.name: hwPowerCentralDCOutputMode
children.description: Mode of central module DC output. Options: 1. highVolMode(1) - indicates the high voltage output mode 2. lowVolMode(2) - indicates the low voltage output mode  Enumeration: 'lowVolMode': 2, 'highVolMode': 1.

children.name: hwPowerRemoteCommState
children.description: Remote power module communications state. Options: 1. normal(1) - indicates the normal state 2. revfault(2) - indicates the receiving of fault 3. sendfault(3) - indicates the sending of fault Enumeration: 'sendfault': 3, 'revfault': 2, 'normal': 1.

children.name: hwPowerRemoteDCInputState
children.description: State of remote module DC input. Options: 1. normal(1) - indicates the normal state 2. lack(2) - indicates that the voltage is underflow  Enumeration: 'lack': 2, 'normal': 1.

children.name: hwPowerRemoteLineCurState
children.description: state of line between central and remote module. Options: 1.normal(1) - indicates the normal state 2.cablejoining(2) - indicates the cable joining 3.curLeakage(3) - indicates the cur Leakage 4.curOver(4) - indicates the cur Over  Enumeration: 'curOver': 4, 'cablejoining': 2, 'curLeakage': 3, 'normal': 1.

children.name: hwPowerRemotePowerState
children.description: state of remote UA60 power. Options: 1. normal(1) - indicates the normal state 2. fault(2) - indicates the faulty state  Enumeration: 'fault': 2, 'normal': 1.

children.name: hwPowerRemoteLineState
children.description: State of line U1. Options: 1. u1state(0) - indicates the power remote line state is u1 state 2. u2state(1) - indicates the power remote line state is u2 state 3. u3state(2) - indicates the power remote line state is u3 state 4. u4state(3) - indicates the power remote line state is u4 state 5. a1state(4) - indicates the power remote line state is a1 state 6. a2state(5) - indicates the power remote line state is a2 state 7. a3state(6) - indicates the power remote line state is a3 state 8. a4state(7) - indicates the power remote line state is a4 state  Bits: 'a3state': 6, 'u4state': 3, 'u1state': 0, 'u3state': 2, 'a2state': 5, 'a1state': 4, 'a4state': 7, 'u2state': 1.

children.name: hwPowerCentralLoadState
children.description: state of central load. Options: 1. normal(1) - indicates the normal state 2. overload(2) - indicates overload 3. nonload(3) - indicates non-load  Enumeration: 'nonload': 3, 'overload': 2, 'normal': 1.

children.name: hwACInfomationTable
children.description: AC infomation table. The table is not supported. The indexes of this table are hwEnvEmuIndex and hwPowerIndex.

children.description: AC infomation table. The table is not supported. The indexes of this entry are hwEnvEmuIndex and hwPowerIndex.

children.name: hwACInfoCommState
children.description: communication state of AC input module. The node is not supported. Options: 1. normal(0) - indicates the communication state of AC is normal 2. fault(1) - indicates the communication state of AC is fault  Enumeration: 'fault': 1, 'normal': 0.

children.name: hwACInfoThunderState
children.description: Thunder's state. The node is not supported. Options: 1. normal(0) - indicates the state of Thunder is normal 2. fault(1) - indicates the state of Thunder is fault  Enumeration: 'fault': 1, 'normal': 0.

children.description: AC input MCB trigger state. The leaf is not supported. Options: 1. normal(0) - indicates the AC input MCB trigger state is normal 2. break-down(1)- indicates the AC input MCB trigger state is break-down  Enumeration: 'break-down': 1, 'normal': 0.
